<br>
Most feel, in its current form, the Wizard Fire pets are not worth the mana to cast.<br>
<br>
<br>
I have a few suggestions that would give most mages a reason to use the fire pet, and hopefully get some good feedback.<br>
<br>
1. This pet will continue to be a wizard pet. So make him ditch melee'ing all together. I believe that the pet, with its current spell line up, would probably be more effective (after we debuffed the mob's of course) if it chain casted the correct spells.<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Correct Spells</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot; means chain casting root, is not what we want. We have Rathe's Son, and the other earth pets to root our mobs. <br>
<br>
While the idea of Chain Stunning was cool, unless the stun is changed to effect 60+ mobs, it's useless. a) Even if the stun level cap were increased, the spells weight in the pets lineup should be decreased. b) We have an air pet that can stun mobs with the best of them already.<br>
<br>
2. Spell Lineup, and Spell Selection by the pet.<br>
-a. Remove Dispell. There are already enough inherent negatives to using pets in groups and on raids. Having the pet dispell cripple, or other debuff should not be one of them<br>
<br>
-b. Biggest, and probably most controversial suggestion. The Level 34 Wiz spell, Concussion.<br>
<br>
Since PoP release, &quot;Man these nukes have a ton of aggro&quot; is not an uncommon phrase to hear when talking to other magicians about Sun Vortex, Black Steel, or Firebolt of Tallon. Mages are the only int casters with out means of lowering their aggro.<br>
<br>
Looking at Concussion, it lowers the caster on the targets hate list by 400.<br>
<br>
I'd suggest making a new &quot;lesser&quot; concussion -200 to hate list. As far as how often the pet should cast this spell, I'd set fairly moderate. Not nearly as often as it nukes. On average, in a 10 min period, I'd say at least 3 casts, but probably no more than 6. Or, once ever 10 or so pet nukes. Im not certian, the numbers would obviously need to be tuned.<br>
<br>
I'm not asking to nuke non-stop till oom with out the mob noticing me, but pets are often prey to the same types of problems some melee classes are complaining about. With huge ae's etc, it would still allow mages to see the same dps they get exping, on raid mobs where they are currently not because the pet dies in the first 15secs of the fight, or after one good ae.<br>
<br>
That's even if it is possible to have a concussion based spell casted by the pet effect the owner position on the mobs hate list.<br>
<br>
